text: Alaska’s September unemployment rate (6.2%) was the highest of any state.
Hawaii’s 2.6% year-over-year increase in GDP was the largest of any state.
September average weekly earnings ranged from Mississippi's $755 to Washington’s $1,198.
Idaho and Utah had the largest increases in house prices between Q2 2018 and Q2 2019.
Kansas’s job growth in September was greater than the US average for the first time since 2012.
California was one of 19 states with a decade-low unemployment rate in September.
Nevada's 4.6% year-over-year increase in public education employment was the largest of any state.
Delaware's GDP growth rate fell below the nation's growth rate for the first time since Q1 2012.
Utah’s 3.3% year-over-year increase in private employment was the largest of any state.
Over the year, state and local public employment decreased the most in New Hampshire.
